Great question — right now your .env is hardcoded to one PC. The cleanest way to handle multiple environments is to have a .env file per environment and pass which one you want at runtime.
Option 1 — Multiple env files (simplest)
bash.env.prod
.env.dev
.env.dr
Each one looks the same but with different IPs/credentials:
PC_IP=10.10.20.24
PC_USER=admin
PC_PASSWORD=yourpassword
Then you pass which environment you want when running the script:
bashpython3 add_erp.py --env prod
python3 add_erp.py --env dr
Option 2 — Single env file with multiple environments
PROD_PC_IP=10.10.20.24
PROD_PC_USER=admin
PROD_PC_PASSWORD=password

DR_PC_IP=10.10.30.24
DR_PC_USER=admin
DR_PC_PASSWORD=password
Option 1 is cleaner and safer — credentials stay separate per environment and you can .gitignore all *.env files.
The change lives in client.py so all your scripts get it automatically — that's the beauty of having the shared client.
